---

!! Effect technique reference

A few of the classic Pokémon holographic-card CSS techniques (glitter, metallic sheen, iridescent shine) can be layered on top of `hover-tilt`'s own tilt/glare via its native attributes (see the Attributes table above — `glareHue`, `glareIntensity`, `blendMode`, `shadow`, etc.) instead of hand-rolled `::before`/`::after` overlays. The table below is a lookup in case a look `hover-tilt` can't produce natively is needed.

|!Effect |!Visual result |!CSS technique |
|Glare |Pointer-tracked light halo — the base of every holo effect |`radial-gradient(farthest-corner circle at var(--mx) var(--my), ...)` — provided by `hover-tilt`, tunable via `glareHue`/`glareIntensity`/`blendMode` |
|Glitter / grain |Scintillating flecks |SVG noise (`feTurbulence`) blended with `screen`, brightness boosted before `contrast()` |
|Metallic / foil sheen |Brushed-metal bands |Angled `repeating-linear-gradient` + `overlay` |
|Iridescent / rainbow shift |Oil-slick shimmer (Trainer Gallery holofoil) |Rainbow `repeating-linear-gradient` + `color-dodge` |
|Holo bars |Classic 90s holo — rainbow stripes + vertical light/dark bars |Two combined `repeating-linear-gradient`s, `soft-light`/`screen`/`overlay` |
|Galaxy / cosmic |Nebula/starfield backdrop |External image + diagonal gradient, `color-dodge`/`color-burn` |
|Radiant crosshatch |Woven/embossed pattern |Two opposed-angle `repeating-linear-gradient`s, `exclusion`/`color-dodge` |
|Gold/metal foil |Warm gold "secret rare" sheen |Metal texture + rainbow, `color-burn`/`darken` |
|3D tilt ✓ |The tilt itself |`rotateX`/`rotateY` following the pointer, `perspective`, `transform-style: preserve-3d` — provided by `hover-tilt` |
|Glow / active shadow ✓ |Light halo on interaction, distinct from glare |`hover-tilt`'s `shadow`/`shadowBlur` attributes |
|Clip-path masking |Confines the holo effect to the illustration, not the frame/text |`clip-path: inset(...)` or `polygon(...)` on the effect layer |

✓ = currently active, via `hover-tilt`'s own attributes rather than custom CSS.

!!! Blend modes used

|!Blend mode |!Effect |!Used for |
|`screen` |Gently lightens, never blows out to pure white |Glitter, classic Holo |
|`color-dodge` |Aggressively lightens (`base ÷ (1 − blend)`), can blow out to white |Iridescent, Galaxy, Gold, Radiant |
|`color-burn` |Opposite of color-dodge — aggressively darkens |Galaxy, Rainbow Secret, Gold |
|`overlay` |Combines multiply (dark areas) + screen (light areas) — boosts existing contrast |Metallic sheen, Holo |
|`hard-light` |Like overlay but driven by the top layer instead of the base — harsher |V, VMAX, VSTAR, Trainer Gallery |
|`soft-light` |Soft version of hard-light — gentle lighten/darken |Holo, V |
|`exclusion` |Like difference but milder — partially inverts overlapping colours |`:after` layers for extra depth, Radiant |
|`multiply` |Darkens by multiplying colours — never lightens |Radiant (woven pattern) |
|`darken` |Keeps the darker of the two colours, pixel by pixel |Gold Secret, Radiant |

`screen`/`overlay`/`soft-light`/`hard-light` are relatively predictable and safe to start with. `color-dodge`/`color-burn`/`exclusion` are more dramatic but far more sensitive to whatever's underneath — worth remembering when a "flat" background makes an effect look weaker than expected.

